And the elephants. of course.

00:30:21.863 --> 00:30:25.519
are a critical element
in these rainforests.

00:30:25.606 --> 00:30:28.304
Elephants are the
bellwether of Africa.

00:30:28.391 --> 00:30:31.133
As elephants go. so
will everything else go.

00:30:31.220 --> 00:30:33.048
They're so big.
they're so dominant.

00:30:36.791 --> 00:30:39.098
they're now so valuable. that
the best way to get a read

00:30:39.185 --> 00:30:41.622
on the natural state of an area.
that should have elephants.

00:30:41.709 --> 00:30:43.232
is to go in and see if
they're there are not.

00:30:43.319 --> 00:30:44.843
usually it's not now.

00:30:47.280 --> 00:30:48.977
If they like to breathe.

00:30:49.064 --> 00:30:50.370
it's probably a good thing
to save the forest. isn't it?

00:30:50.457 --> 00:30:51.937
But maybe they don't
think about that.

00:30:52.024 --> 00:30:54.461
They want a stable
climate you have to look

00:30:54.548 --> 00:30:56.593
at the integrity
and the function.

00:30:56.680 --> 00:30:58.552
it's called ecosystem services.

00:31:00.249 --> 00:31:02.208
- [Jane] The elephants
open up the forests

00:31:02.295 --> 00:31:04.471
so that new life can grow.

00:31:04.558 --> 00:31:06.908
they transport
seeds in their dung.

00:31:06.995 --> 00:31:09.737
Chimpanzees do exactly
the same; they take seeds

00:31:09.824 --> 00:31:11.870
and spread them
around in the forest.

00:31:13.001 --> 00:31:15.743
[peaceful music]

00:31:19.573 --> 00:31:22.706
[elephants trumpeting]

00:31:24.143 --> 00:31:26.972
[leaves rustling]

00:31:28.103 --> 00:31:32.194
- Elephants disperse
more seeds individually.

00:31:32.281 --> 00:31:35.545
of more species of
trees and other plants.

00:31:35.632 --> 00:31:39.288
further than any other animal.

00:31:39.375 --> 00:31:40.855
And they do that
wherever they live.

00:31:40.942 --> 00:31:44.293
So. 50 countries. 37 in Africa.

00:31:44.380 --> 00:31:48.863
13 in Asia. have natural
elephant populations.

00:31:48.950 --> 00:31:50.821
[mysterious music]

00:31:50.909 --> 00:31:54.738
- [Mike] Elephants in particular
are unique in the sense

00:31:54.825 --> 00:31:58.525
that their digestive
process is so intense

00:31:58.612 --> 00:32:00.875
there are seeds
from certain trees

00:32:00.962 --> 00:32:03.356
that will not germinate
unless they've passed

00:32:03.443 --> 00:32:04.748
through an elephant's gut.

00:32:07.447 --> 00:32:10.798
So. the reason that people
kill trees in Africa

00:32:10.885 --> 00:32:12.887
is because they want
the carbon that's stored

00:32:12.974 --> 00:32:14.715
in the tree as a fuel.

00:32:14.802 --> 00:32:17.022
They want to use
it for charcoal.

00:32:17.109 --> 00:32:18.501
[smoke hissing]

00:32:18.588 --> 00:32:21.461
The forest is an
extremely valuable asset

00:32:21.548 --> 00:32:24.029
that the government has to
try and keep its hands off.

00:32:24.116 --> 00:32:26.553
If they don't and that
forest disappears.

00:32:26.640 --> 00:32:29.295
we will never keep
climate to two degrees.

00:32:31.819 --> 00:32:33.081
If you value the forest.

00:32:33.168 --> 00:32:35.040
protect the gardeners
of the forest.

00:32:35.127 --> 00:32:36.998
They are not ornaments.
they are not things

00:32:37.085 --> 00:32:39.131
to go and see on holiday.

00:32:39.218 --> 00:32:43.048
Every gorilla. every
elephant. every howler monkey

00:32:43.135 --> 00:32:46.051
in Latin America. or
tapir. are working for us.

00:32:46.138 --> 00:32:48.662
dispersing seeds for
the trees of tomorrow.

00:32:48.749 --> 00:32:50.664
And if we want
those carbon stores

00:32:50.751 --> 00:32:54.929
and those rainwater-generating
forests to continue

00:32:55.016 --> 00:32:56.757
into the next century.
we have to make sure

00:32:56.844 --> 00:32:59.847
that the seeds are being
sown today to do that job.

00:33:02.241 --> 00:33:03.546
People think there's a forest

00:33:03.633 --> 00:33:05.418
and then you put
some animals in. no.

00:33:05.505 --> 00:33:08.160
The animals and the
trees and the bacteria

00:33:08.247 --> 00:33:10.640
are all part of that
forest ecosystem.

00:33:10.727 --> 00:33:12.077
And one of the
things that gorillas

00:33:12.164 --> 00:33:15.123
do spectacularly well
is produce manure.

00:33:15.210 --> 00:33:18.648
A gorilla will eat and
produce something like.

00:33:18.735 --> 00:33:22.000
between 10 and 20 kilos
of dung every day.

00:33:22.087 --> 00:33:23.349
That's about one
hundred kilos a week.

00:33:23.436 --> 00:33:26.395
In 10 weeks that's
a ton of manure

00:33:26.482 --> 00:33:27.788
being spread around the forest.

00:33:27.875 --> 00:33:30.095
And in that manure are seeds.

00:33:30.182 --> 00:33:32.140
Elephants are even
more important

00:33:32.227 --> 00:33:33.620
as gardeners of the forest.

00:33:33.707 --> 00:33:35.491
If gorillas are the
gardeners of the forest.

00:33:35.578 --> 00:33:37.841
elephants are the
mega-gardeners.
because they're so big.

00:33:39.843 --> 00:33:41.845
But we're so taken
aback by how powerful

00:33:41.932 --> 00:33:44.631
they are. we think
they're indestructible.

00:33:44.718 --> 00:33:47.460
[leaves rustling]

00:33:47.547 --> 00:33:50.115
As human development has
grown and elephant habitat

00:33:50.202 --> 00:33:53.509
has shrunk. the elephants
are constantly coming up

00:33:53.596 --> 00:33:56.295
against people who
are unfriendly. who
are chasing them out

00:33:56.382 --> 00:33:57.905
of their crops. who are trying

00:33:57.992 --> 00:34:01.126
to defend their livelihood
from the elephants.

00:34:01.213 --> 00:34:03.041
And the elephants
are seen as an enemy.

00:34:03.128 --> 00:34:04.825
And that the latest
manifestation of this.

00:34:04.912 --> 00:34:08.089
that I've experienced
is charcoal.

00:34:08.176 --> 00:34:09.743
Because for most
families in Africa

00:34:09.830 --> 00:34:11.614
they don't have electricity.
they don't have gas.

00:34:11.701 --> 00:34:15.009
If they got to cook. they
need either wood or charcoal.

00:34:15.096 --> 00:34:16.924
In many cities.
the charcoal trade

00:34:17.011 --> 00:34:19.970
is a multi-million dollar
business. which means anyone

00:34:20.058 --> 00:34:23.452
who can pay people a pittance
to go and cut down trees.

00:34:23.539 --> 00:34:26.890
or even just branches of
trees. build a charcoal kiln

00:34:26.977 --> 00:34:28.544
and bring out a few
bags of charcoal.

00:34:28.631 --> 00:34:30.155
they'll be paid a few
dollars. And that charcoal

00:34:30.242 --> 00:34:32.070
is worth a lot of
money in the city.

00:34:34.594 --> 00:34:36.770
The first day we went out
in the forest reserve.

00:34:36.857 --> 00:34:39.338
we saw three
charcoal operations.

00:34:39.425 --> 00:34:41.209
The elephants were right
next to the charcoal

00:34:41.296 --> 00:34:43.646
and were obviously agitated.

00:34:43.733 --> 00:34:45.822
The matriarch clearly felt

00:34:45.909 --> 00:34:47.650
that we were posing
a threat to them.

00:34:47.737 --> 00:34:49.261
She started running towards us.

00:34:49.348 --> 00:34:50.697
I didn't want to
be hit from behind.

00:34:50.784 --> 00:34:52.525
so I turned around
and I was rumbling.

00:34:52.612 --> 00:34:53.961
sort of a [imitates rumbling].

00:34:56.920 --> 00:34:58.487
as we do when we
approach the elephants.

00:34:58.574 --> 00:35:01.186
She was really moving. [laughs]

00:35:02.839 --> 00:35:05.407
I was still running backwards.
still trying to placate her

00:35:05.494 --> 00:35:09.194
when she hit me and I put
my hands up to her face.

00:35:09.281 --> 00:35:14.286
And when I turned to face
her and then the camera

00:35:15.417 --> 00:35:17.027
hit the elephant's
face against my hand.

00:35:17.115 --> 00:35:18.638
But that turned the camera off.

00:35:19.813 --> 00:35:21.510
And it left me on
my hands and knees

00:35:21.597 --> 00:35:24.078
when I completed the backward
roll. under the elephant.

00:35:24.165 --> 00:35:26.080
And she started playing
football with me.

00:35:26.167 --> 00:35:28.735
After five seconds.
one of the kicks

00:35:28.822 --> 00:35:31.303
happened to knock the
camera and turn it on again.

00:35:34.480 --> 00:35:37.309
[camera clicking]

00:35:39.702 --> 00:35:40.747
[elephant trumpets]

00:35:40.834 --> 00:35:41.878
A second later. you hear

00:35:41.965 --> 00:35:44.620
[gun firing]

00:35:44.707 --> 00:35:48.233
which is the rangers who
had fired a shot. in the air

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:49.625
and the elephant fled.

00:35:49.712 --> 00:35:52.541
She came to chase
the humans away.

00:35:52.628 --> 00:35:54.587
who were hassling her family.

00:35:54.674 --> 00:35:57.459
Now in human society. we
give people like that medals.

00:35:59.331 --> 00:36:02.334
[elephant rumbling]

00:36:17.044 --> 00:36:20.003
- The growth in the human
population and its footprint.

00:36:20.090 --> 00:36:23.268
is a major threat. probably
the single biggest threat.

00:36:23.355 --> 00:36:26.184
to wildlife persisting
into the long term.

00:36:26.271 --> 00:36:29.274
Simply because it doesn't
have to take all the land away

00:36:29.361 --> 00:36:32.059
from wildlife. it fragments it.

00:36:32.146 --> 00:36:35.105
We take the best bits. we leave
the worst bits for wildlife.

00:36:35.193 --> 00:36:38.239
Now. a population that used
to live in a particular area

00:36:38.326 --> 00:36:39.980
is two populations separated

00:36:40.067 --> 00:36:41.851
by human settlements
in the middle.

00:36:41.938 --> 00:36:45.681
So. they can't literally get
in contact with each other.

00:36:45.768 --> 00:36:48.815
So one of the biggest
challenges out there is the fact

00:36:48.902 --> 00:36:51.296
that the human population.
currently about seven

00:36:51.383 --> 00:36:53.907
and a bit billion people on
this planet. is going to rise

00:36:53.994 --> 00:36:57.302
to eleven billion people
by the end of this century.

00:36:57.389 --> 00:37:00.218
And the question then is.
is there room for wildlife?

00:37:02.394 --> 00:37:06.441
- There is an actual movement
in conservation to focus

00:37:06.528 --> 00:37:10.315
on population reduction in
humans as an indirect way

00:37:10.402 --> 00:37:13.100
to improve wildlife
conservation.

00:37:13.187 --> 00:37:15.668
So. one approach has
been for conservationists

00:37:15.755 --> 00:37:20.760
to teach population control and
offer reproductive education

00:37:21.848 --> 00:37:23.676
to the women who
live in the villages.

00:37:23.763 --> 00:37:27.288
So. they've seen the
childbirth. you know.

00:37:27.375 --> 00:37:30.030
the growth has flat-lined
in those villages.

00:37:36.689 --> 00:37:39.692
- [Narrator] The
desert elephants of
Namibia's Kunene Region

00:37:39.779 --> 00:37:42.738
are one of only two
populations of desert elephants

00:37:42.825 --> 00:37:46.307
in the world. the other
is in Mali. North Africa.

00:37:46.394 --> 00:37:49.963
approximately 150
individuals remain here.

00:37:50.790 --> 00:37:52.357
- Why am I pessimistic?

00:37:52.444 --> 00:37:54.924
Just because of the
numbers of humans on earth.

00:37:58.798 --> 00:38:00.539
And elephants are disappearing

00:38:00.626 --> 00:38:05.239
and I can't just wave
a magic wand or jump

00:38:05.326 --> 00:38:07.633
to action and save them.

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:10.026
That's part of being
wildlife biologists

00:38:10.113 --> 00:38:15.118
is you see a lot of death and
you get to see the rare birth

00:38:16.294 --> 00:38:19.993
that balances out all
the. all the death.

00:38:21.342 --> 00:38:23.518
It was a life changing
experience for me.

00:38:23.605 --> 00:38:25.738
I knew I wanted to
work with elephants.

00:38:25.825 --> 00:38:28.306
We thought originally
we'd go back to Zimbabwe

00:38:28.393 --> 00:38:30.569
and work there.
but then Zimbabwe

00:38:30.656 --> 00:38:33.963
went extremely
downhill. very fast.

00:38:34.877 --> 00:38:36.531
- Yeah.

00:38:36.618 --> 00:38:37.967
- In Zimbabwe. you know when
our friends would go out

00:38:38.054 --> 00:38:41.275
on an anti-poaching
patrol. suddenly this

00:38:41.362 --> 00:38:44.060
was a military operation
in the national park.

00:38:44.147 --> 00:38:45.758
where they would
hand out the weapons

00:38:45.845 --> 00:38:48.108
and their lives were
out there on the line.

00:38:48.195 --> 00:38:51.894
And so it takes that level
of commitment. of individuals

00:38:51.981 --> 00:38:56.986
and a commitment of society.
in order to turn it around.

00:38:58.510 --> 00:39:01.817
They're a lot of people that
do value the elephants there.

00:39:01.904 --> 00:39:04.777
And then there are a number of
people. like in any society.

00:39:04.864 --> 00:39:07.562
they won't appreciate
what they have or had.

00:39:07.649 --> 00:39:08.737
until it's gone.

00:39:10.173 --> 00:39:11.784
- The bigger problem
we're dealing with

00:39:11.871 --> 00:39:16.223
with desert elephants is
not so much ivory poaching.

00:39:16.310 --> 00:39:21.315
it's attitudes of the people
who live with elephants.

00:39:22.403 --> 00:39:25.188
who pay the price.
through destroyed crops

00:39:25.275 --> 00:39:29.149
or. you know. untimely
death of relatives

00:39:29.236 --> 00:39:32.413
or friends from elephants
or lions. whatever it is.

00:39:33.632 --> 00:39:36.461
[somber music]

00:39:36.548 --> 00:39:39.551
So. we need people
to go to Namibia.

00:39:39.638 --> 00:39:42.423
spend their tourist dollars.
pay the local people

00:39:42.510 --> 00:39:45.948
to tell them about
their lifestyle.

00:39:46.035 --> 00:39:48.734
make the elephants
worthwhile to those people.

00:39:48.821 --> 00:39:51.345
by sharing the wealth
that we have here.

00:39:51.432 --> 00:39:54.696
with those people there and
then elephants will be valued.

00:39:56.394 --> 00:40:01.181
In 2012. we went to Africa
and we got to a village

00:40:01.268 --> 00:40:03.444
that we know very well.

00:40:03.531 --> 00:40:07.492
Just two days after.
one of our elephants.

00:40:07.579 --> 00:40:10.059
one of our known
elephants. had been killed

00:40:10.146 --> 00:40:13.367
by the authorities for
being a problem animal.

00:40:13.454 --> 00:40:15.413
And we didn't know
which elephant it was.

00:40:15.500 --> 00:40:18.459
but we arrived there
and all that was left

00:40:18.546 --> 00:40:20.983
of his carcass was an ear.

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:24.596
I looked at my ID book of all
the elephants and who's who.

00:40:24.683 --> 00:40:27.294
based on their ear
patterns and I said

00:40:27.381 --> 00:40:31.907
"Oh. this is M7. Mr. Sneaky".

00:40:33.474 --> 00:40:38.044
The local guy who was
showing us the carcass said.

00:40:38.131 --> 00:40:41.264
"Well. the meat was given
to the local people to eat."

00:40:41.351 --> 00:40:42.614
and he said.

00:40:42.701 --> 00:40:44.267
"Don't you like elephant meat?"

00:40:45.486 --> 00:40:47.706
And I said. "I would
never eat an elephant.

00:40:47.793 --> 00:40:50.099
"it would be like
eating a family member."

00:40:51.274 --> 00:40:53.189
And he thought that was
the strangest thing.

00:40:56.366 --> 00:40:58.368
We were feeling
extremely discouraged

00:40:58.456 --> 00:41:01.807
and decided we're done.

00:41:01.894 --> 00:41:04.549
Let's just go and say
goodbye to the elephants

00:41:04.636 --> 00:41:05.506
and we're done.

00:41:08.988 --> 00:41:12.426
The next day we came upon our
favorite group of elephants.

00:41:12.513 --> 00:41:17.475
the tuskless matriarch.
and the teenage daughter.

00:41:18.911 --> 00:41:22.915
whose name is Dorothy.
was showing some breasts.

00:41:24.133 --> 00:41:26.701
Dorothy starts to
act very strangely

00:41:26.788 --> 00:41:31.010
and all of a sudden out
comes this birth sac

00:41:31.097 --> 00:41:35.014
and poosh on the ground.
a baby elephant is born.

00:41:35.101 --> 00:41:37.756
[elephant rumbles]

00:41:37.843 --> 00:41:41.237
[gentle. peaceful music]

00:42:17.273 --> 00:42:20.102
[elephant rumbles]

00:42:43.648 --> 00:42:45.171
We both said. "This is it".

00:42:45.258 --> 00:42:47.956
"How can we give
up at this point?"

00:42:48.043 --> 00:42:50.089
- We're all in again. all in.

00:42:50.176 --> 00:42:52.744
[laughing]

00:42:52.831 --> 00:42:54.484
We're going for
it. laying it out

00:42:54.572 --> 00:42:58.358
on the line in order to
turn the tide on extinction.

00:42:59.751 --> 00:43:02.275
[upbeat music]

00:43:05.278 --> 00:43:06.584
- [Narrator] Humans and wildlife

00:43:06.671 --> 00:43:08.760
compete for natural resources.

00:43:10.196 --> 00:43:13.199
Male elephants more often
raid crops than do females

00:43:13.286 --> 00:43:16.681
in order to gain size and
reproductive advantage.

00:43:16.768 --> 00:43:20.815
These crop raiders are then
considered problem elephants.

00:43:23.992 --> 00:43:27.039
- In case of human wildlife
conflict. we always follow up.

00:43:27.126 --> 00:43:28.954
If an elephant comes into
a farm and you kill it.

00:43:29.041 --> 00:43:30.738
you can't be charged.

00:43:30.825 --> 00:43:34.350
It's the only income that
farmer might have for that year.

00:43:34.437 --> 00:43:35.961
He's relying on it
to feed his family.

00:43:36.048 --> 00:43:39.399
He's relying on it to
educate his kids. whatever.

00:43:39.486 --> 00:43:41.227
So. in two minutes an
elephant will go in there

00:43:41.314 --> 00:43:43.490
and destroy a whole
year's worth of crops.

00:43:44.839 --> 00:43:47.581
So. you can understand
why you get out of bed

00:43:47.668 --> 00:43:49.757
in the middle of the night and
throw a spear at an elephant.

00:43:49.844 --> 00:43:53.108
So. these are spears that
we've confiscated off poachers.

00:43:54.936 --> 00:43:59.593
Again. they poison the
blade so when it goes in.

00:43:59.680 --> 00:44:02.509
it's not only the spear
that does the damage.

00:44:02.596 --> 00:44:04.772
it's the poison that
finishes it off.

00:44:04.859 --> 00:44:07.601
The worst is when you dig
one out of a dead elephant.

00:44:07.688 --> 00:44:09.472
Sometimes it kills
it quite quickly.

00:44:09.559 --> 00:44:12.171
I say quickly. 10. 15 minutes.

00:44:12.258 --> 00:44:16.392
Sometimes it takes
days. sometimes months.

00:44:16.479 --> 00:44:17.655
Poisoning spears is a new thing.

00:44:17.742 --> 00:44:19.265
It never used to happen before.

00:44:19.352 --> 00:44:21.093
It's a new technique.

00:44:21.180 --> 00:44:23.617
But also they're
using pesticides now.

00:44:23.704 --> 00:44:25.445
They've ramped it up.

00:44:25.532 --> 00:44:27.273
There's pesticides
available on the market

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:30.015
and you can just go buy that
from the veterinary shop.

00:44:30.102 --> 00:44:32.147
soak your arrow or
your spear in it.

00:44:32.234 --> 00:44:34.672
and it's more lethal than
the traditional poison.

00:44:37.283 --> 00:44:40.634
[elephant screeching]

00:44:40.721 --> 00:44:43.028
- Human-elephant conflict
is a huge problem

00:44:43.115 --> 00:44:46.945
in Laikipia County
and the levels of
human-elephant conflict

00:44:47.032 --> 00:44:49.469
are probably amongst the worst
in the whole of East Africa.

00:44:49.556 --> 00:44:51.819
We got a call from one of
our scouts in the field.

00:44:51.906 --> 00:44:54.648
who gave us some
information about elephants

00:44:54.735 --> 00:44:57.477
being stuck in a dam.

00:44:57.564 --> 00:44:59.479
You had seven bull
elephants who had crop

00:44:59.566 --> 00:45:00.828
raided the night before.

00:45:03.613 --> 00:45:05.790
And once we closer. it
became clear these elephants

00:45:05.877 --> 00:45:08.140
weren't stuck at all.
but that the community

00:45:08.227 --> 00:45:09.924
was actually holding
them hostage.

00:45:11.143 --> 00:45:12.666
I mean you had 400
people screaming

00:45:12.753 --> 00:45:14.320
and yelling in all
directions and the elephants

00:45:14.407 --> 00:45:16.670
didn't know which way to go.

00:45:16.757 --> 00:45:19.064
[screaming]

00:45:21.370 --> 00:45:23.024
[helicopter whirring]

00:45:23.111 --> 00:45:25.766
And the arrival of this
helicopter sent the population

00:45:25.853 --> 00:45:29.204
into a frenzy because they
wanted to harvest the meat.

00:45:29.291 --> 00:45:31.206
so at least they
would have something.

00:45:32.642 --> 00:45:33.905
People would prevent them
from leaving. you know.

00:45:33.992 --> 00:45:35.428
by shouting or by
throwing stones

00:45:35.515 --> 00:45:37.822
and by driving
fire towards them.

00:45:37.909 --> 00:45:41.086
This elephant made a
desperate attempt to escape.

00:45:43.436 --> 00:45:45.264
And it charged
into the shallows.

00:45:45.351 --> 00:45:49.094
Now you had an elephant
on the run amongst people.

00:45:51.226 --> 00:45:53.272
This act of bravery. I suppose.

00:45:53.359 --> 00:45:55.056
encouraged the other elephants

00:45:55.143 --> 00:45:58.364
so they managed to get out
as well. once the helicopter

00:45:58.451 --> 00:46:00.627
pushed the people and
cleared the way for them.

00:46:02.629 --> 00:46:04.631
It's really tough for
conservationists because people

00:46:04.718 --> 00:46:06.285
look at us and say.

00:46:06.372 --> 00:46:07.590
"Ah. you know we only
care about the elephants.

00:46:07.677 --> 00:46:08.461
"We don't care
about the people."

00:46:08.548 --> 00:46:09.984
This is not true.

00:46:10.071 --> 00:46:12.770
but these are the
perceptions that go around.

00:46:13.858 --> 00:46:15.555
[splashing]

00:46:15.642 --> 00:46:16.948
- You can't ignore
that human need

00:46:17.035 --> 00:46:18.776
in solving the
conservation problems.

00:46:19.994 --> 00:46:22.388
This generation is the
generation that's now

00:46:22.475 --> 00:46:24.607
in conflict for the first time

00:46:24.694 --> 00:46:27.088
in many. many. many generations.

00:46:29.743 --> 00:46:31.049
[splashing]

00:46:31.136 --> 00:46:32.572
It's not a cultural
norm for them to be

00:46:32.659 --> 00:46:34.443
in conflict with wildlife.

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:37.664
They didn't conquer the
wilderness the way the pioneers

00:46:37.751 --> 00:46:39.361
did in North America perhaps.

00:46:39.448 --> 00:46:40.928
where there were dangerous
animals that were killed

00:46:41.015 --> 00:46:43.452
to make the land
safe for families.

00:46:43.539 --> 00:46:46.238
If you can work with
them to see the wildlife

00:46:46.325 --> 00:46:49.328
and the wilderness as an
asset. there is still time.

00:46:49.415 --> 00:46:51.678
This challenge that
wildlife faces now

00:46:51.765 --> 00:46:53.114
is not about changing wildlife.

00:46:53.201 --> 00:46:55.247
The group that has to
change is the humans.

00:46:55.334 --> 00:46:58.250
[crowd chattering]

00:47:01.383 --> 00:47:02.776
- [Narrator]
Human-elephant conflict

00:47:02.863 --> 00:47:05.039
threatens elephant survival.

00:47:05.126 --> 00:47:08.042
Translocating. or moving.
'problem' elephants

00:47:08.129 --> 00:47:10.392
is one conservation strategy.

00:47:10.479 --> 00:47:14.527
But translocation intensifies
human-elephant conflict

00:47:14.614 --> 00:47:16.181
and increases elephant deaths.

00:47:17.922 --> 00:47:21.142
[elephant crying]:

00:47:21.229 --> 00:47:24.754
- Another example of how
we know elephants behave

00:47:24.842 --> 00:47:26.408
when they don't have
their elders around

00:47:26.495 --> 00:47:29.194
is from young elephants
that have been translocated.

00:47:29.281 --> 00:47:31.936
So. they move in
elephants that perhaps

00:47:32.023 --> 00:47:34.677
have seen their
family members culled.

00:47:34.764 --> 00:47:39.073
all of the family members
killed in another park

00:47:39.160 --> 00:47:40.422
in South Africa. where they felt

00:47:40.509 --> 00:47:42.163
there were too many elephants.

00:47:42.250 --> 00:47:44.252
So. they kill all the adults.
they take the youngsters

00:47:44.339 --> 00:47:46.776
and move them out
to another park.

00:47:47.777 --> 00:47:50.868
[elephants screaming]

00:48:00.703 --> 00:48:02.357
- My name is Barbara Wiseman.

00:48:02.444 --> 00:48:03.837
and I'm the
international president

00:48:03.924 --> 00:48:06.361
of the Lawrence Anthony
Earth organization.

00:48:06.448 --> 00:48:08.668
Lawrence had told me there
was a troublesome herd.

00:48:08.755 --> 00:48:11.976
they hated people. because
people had killed most

00:48:12.063 --> 00:48:13.803
of the herd off.

00:48:13.891 --> 00:48:15.762
- If I didn't take them they
were all going to get put down.

00:48:15.849 --> 00:48:18.156
So. I said. "Sure.
absolutely. we'll take them".

00:48:18.243 --> 00:48:19.505
- [Barbara] The
matriarch knew how

00:48:19.592 --> 00:48:21.507
to push over an electric fence

00:48:21.594 --> 00:48:24.075
and short it out and
escape with her herd.

00:48:25.598 --> 00:48:29.123
They had game rangers. the
game rangers all had guns.

00:48:29.210 --> 00:48:31.256
some of them were
intending to kill them.

00:48:32.561 --> 00:48:34.999
Finally. the helicopter
pilot got them back.

00:48:35.086 --> 00:48:36.435
[helicopter whirring]

00:48:36.522 --> 00:48:37.915
- [Lawrence] The
authorities just said.

00:48:38.002 --> 00:48:39.394
"Don't have anything to do

00:48:39.481 --> 00:48:41.048
"with the elephant when
they're in the boma.

00:48:41.135 --> 00:48:42.528
"just leave them."

00:48:42.615 --> 00:48:44.704
And last time we did
that. they broke out.

00:48:44.791 --> 00:48:47.011
So. I figured you know
somehow they have to learn

00:48:47.098 --> 00:48:49.839
to trust at least
one human being.

00:48:51.276 --> 00:48:53.539
[dramatic music]

00:48:53.626 --> 00:48:57.195
- [Barbara] So. he decided to
stay with them 24 hours a day.

00:48:57.282 --> 00:48:59.806
for as long as it took.
to get them used to him.

00:49:02.156 --> 00:49:07.161
And every morning the matriarch
would stand at the fence

00:49:08.641 --> 00:49:09.947
looking like she was going
to make a break for it.

00:49:11.600 --> 00:49:13.472
If an elephant breaks
through an electric fence

00:49:13.559 --> 00:49:16.736
with their body once.
they realize that they can

00:49:16.823 --> 00:49:20.044
withstand the
charge long enough.

00:49:20.131 --> 00:49:22.133
that you can never
hold them again.

00:49:24.657 --> 00:49:27.703
And Lawrence would stand
just outside of her reach

00:49:27.790 --> 00:49:28.704
and talk to her.

00:49:30.445 --> 00:49:34.754
- [Lawrence] Hello. my baby
beautiful. hello. my bubba.

00:49:34.841 --> 00:49:37.322
Hello. my beautiful girl.

00:49:37.409 --> 00:49:42.414
Yes. come on. come
on. come. bubba.

00:49:44.677 --> 00:49:45.939
- [Barbara] Lawrence
was staying with them.

00:49:46.026 --> 00:49:47.723
they were incredibly hostile.

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:49.464
If they could have got him.

00:49:49.551 --> 00:49:50.813
they would have pulled him in

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:52.990
and stomped him into the ground.

00:49:53.077 --> 00:49:57.168
So. after three weeks of this.
one day Lawrence described it

00:49:57.255 --> 00:50:00.127
as though all of the
hostility turned off.

00:50:00.214 --> 00:50:03.609
like you would turn off a
light switch. just boom.

00:50:03.696 --> 00:50:07.004
- [Lawrence] Everything had
gone calm and the matriarch

00:50:07.091 --> 00:50:08.396
walked up to me.

00:50:08.483 --> 00:50:10.094
And she approached
me and I backed off.

00:50:10.181 --> 00:50:11.704
and she stood there.
very benignly.

00:50:11.791 --> 00:50:15.229
ears down. great
emotion around her.

00:50:15.316 --> 00:50:16.926
Eventually I stepped
forward to the fence.

00:50:17.014 --> 00:50:18.624
and she put her trunk
through and touched me.

00:50:18.711 --> 00:50:20.843
And I thought. "Well. that's
it. I'll let them out."

00:50:22.062 --> 00:50:25.109
[peaceful music]

00:50:25.196 --> 00:50:28.938
[elephant rumbling]

00:50:29.026 --> 00:50:31.202
[shouting]

00:50:31.289 --> 00:50:33.421
- [Barbara] They could be a
mile away. but if they heard it

00:50:33.508 --> 00:50:37.121
was Lawrence they would come
like puppy dogs to see him.

00:50:39.732 --> 00:50:41.995
- [Lawrence] Whenever I come
back. the day I come back.

00:50:42.082 --> 00:50:44.780
when I drive in. they'll
come up to the house.

00:50:50.525 --> 00:50:53.398
The herd emanates something.
it emanates something

00:50:53.485 --> 00:50:54.790
at a different level.

00:50:54.877 --> 00:50:57.054
Being in proximity
to a herd. apart

00:50:57.141 --> 00:50:59.273
from watching the
physical manifestations

00:50:59.360 --> 00:51:03.408
and their body languages. you
actually get an emanation.

00:51:12.721 --> 00:51:14.419
- The elephants had been
living with Lawrence

00:51:14.506 --> 00:51:16.638
for about 12 years
when he passed away.

00:51:16.725 --> 00:51:18.684
The elephants were
about 12 miles

00:51:18.771 --> 00:51:21.991
from the house. and
they perceived it.

00:51:22.079 --> 00:51:27.084
And they walked to the
house. in mourning. very sort

00:51:28.215 --> 00:51:30.261
of sad aspect; and when
they got to the house.

00:51:30.348 --> 00:51:32.393
just very agitated they
were usually very calm.

00:51:32.480 --> 00:51:35.353
very peaceful. but they
were very agitated.

00:51:35.440 --> 00:51:38.921
And they stayed around the
house for about three hours

00:51:39.008 --> 00:51:40.706
and then they disappeared.

00:51:40.793 --> 00:51:43.970
Interestingly. every year
since then. on the anniversary

00:51:44.057 --> 00:51:46.712
of his death. they've
returned to the house.

00:51:46.799 --> 00:51:49.976
[elephant trumpets. lion roars]

00:51:53.284 --> 00:51:57.505
- You know. lions are not
getting the attention.

00:51:57.592 --> 00:51:59.333
It's up to us people
in the field to try

00:51:59.420 --> 00:52:00.552
and stop the poisoning.

00:52:00.639 --> 00:52:02.554
It's all about the cattle.

00:52:02.641 --> 00:52:07.036
People don't boma. corral
their stock. properly anymore.

00:52:07.124 --> 00:52:08.777
So lions get in.

00:52:08.864 --> 00:52:11.650
There's a lot more cattle.
there's a lot more people.

00:52:13.304 --> 00:52:16.089
- So now we have a
surge in cattle numbers

00:52:16.176 --> 00:52:18.874
and when they start to
invade the wildlife space.

00:52:18.961 --> 00:52:20.485
that's when you get conflict.

00:52:20.572 --> 00:52:22.574
And then of course. people.
if they lose a goat.

00:52:22.661 --> 00:52:24.576
or a cow. they retaliate.

00:52:24.663 --> 00:52:27.013
And they go after the hyena
or the leopard or the lion.

00:52:27.100 --> 00:52:30.103
And there are only
20.000 lions in Africa.

00:52:33.498 --> 00:52:37.284
- Well. I was a surfer at the
coast and my dream of going

00:52:37.371 --> 00:52:39.634
into the bush and playing Tarzan

00:52:39.721 --> 00:52:43.899
and becoming a great game
man. wildlife man in Africa.

00:52:43.986 --> 00:52:47.381
was sort of lost in the
waves and the lifestyle.

00:52:48.600 --> 00:52:50.210
When I met Joy. I
had written to her

00:52:50.297 --> 00:52:51.951
and said "Have you got any
openings. and she said.

00:52:52.038 --> 00:52:55.302
"Well. I have nothing
going. but I know my husband

00:52:55.389 --> 00:52:58.610
"is looking for someone.
because his previous assistant

00:52:58.697 --> 00:53:01.874
has just been killed
by one his lions."

00:53:01.961 --> 00:53:03.310
And I thought.
"Great. that sounds

00:53:03.397 --> 00:53:05.269
"like the sort of
thing I want to do."

00:53:06.792 --> 00:53:10.970
When I joined George. his
pride was down from 11 to 3.

00:53:12.058 --> 00:53:14.408
And amongst them were
two females: Lisa.

00:53:14.495 --> 00:53:17.803
who was very affectionate.
Juma. whom you couldn't handle.

00:53:17.890 --> 00:53:20.980
because she'd been very
badly treated on capture

00:53:21.067 --> 00:53:24.288
and Christian. the lion
that came from England.

00:53:24.375 --> 00:53:27.073
[dramatic music]

00:53:48.050 --> 00:53:50.488
Christian was coming
up to two years old.

00:53:50.575 --> 00:53:52.707
he really didn't know
what he was doing.

00:53:52.794 --> 00:53:54.187
I didn't have a clue.

00:53:55.928 --> 00:53:58.713
Christian and I grew up
together. and got into all sorts

00:53:58.800 --> 00:54:00.759
of scrapes. had
all sorts of fun.

00:54:00.846 --> 00:54:03.065
and we taught each other
everything we knew.

00:54:04.110 --> 00:54:06.547
They're very loving and they're.

00:54:06.634 --> 00:54:08.462
you can form a very close
relationship with them.

00:54:08.549 --> 00:54:09.855
but you got to watch it.

00:54:09.942 --> 00:54:11.596
It's an occupational hazard.

00:54:11.683 --> 00:54:15.861
You know. racing drivers have
car crashes and you know.

00:54:15.948 --> 00:54:19.212
painters fall off ladders.
and it's no worse than that.

00:54:19.299 --> 00:54:21.475
It makes for a better story.

00:54:21.562 --> 00:54:22.520
- [Director] Is this
one of the lions

00:54:22.607 --> 00:54:23.869
that you guys were raising?

00:54:23.956 --> 00:54:25.305
- No. it was part
of a wild pride

00:54:25.392 --> 00:54:27.046
that we brought up
when their mother died.

00:54:27.133 --> 00:54:29.222
Not a lion we'd ever handled.

00:54:29.309 --> 00:54:30.354
But then eventually he got me.

00:54:30.441 --> 00:54:32.051
All I could do was go fetal.

00:54:32.138 --> 00:54:34.445
I could hardly...I kept
sort of coming and going.

00:54:36.882 --> 00:54:39.885
And then he got me through
the neck and strangled.

00:54:39.972 --> 00:54:42.540
George did the most
wonderful things

00:54:42.627 --> 00:54:45.804
because what he did with the
respect and the understanding

00:54:45.891 --> 00:54:47.284
that he had for
these wild animals

00:54:47.371 --> 00:54:48.894
and the way he carried it out

00:54:48.981 --> 00:54:51.244
and just the whole
toughness of it.

00:54:51.331 --> 00:54:54.247
I mean. there he
was day and night.

00:54:54.334 --> 00:54:57.119
you know. 365 days a
year out in the bush

00:54:57.206 --> 00:54:58.512
with a pride of lions.

00:55:03.169 --> 00:55:04.953
And they're lovely.

00:55:18.663 --> 00:55:21.013
[flamingos honking]

00:55:28.368 --> 00:55:30.631
So. I feel very
sad. I never thought

00:55:30.718 --> 00:55:33.460
that in the short period
of time. nearly 50 years.

00:55:33.547 --> 00:55:38.073
that I've been in Africa. I
would see wild animals go down.

00:55:38.160 --> 00:55:41.120
you know. to such low
levels and be regarded

00:55:41.207 --> 00:55:43.340
in such a low light.

00:55:48.301 --> 00:55:51.043
[tires on pavement]

00:55:52.479 --> 00:55:56.265
It's just horrific how
things can change so fast.

00:55:57.441 --> 00:55:58.920
You know. it's just
people against wildlife

00:55:59.007 --> 00:56:01.706
and looking after
wildlife isn't difficult.

00:56:01.793 --> 00:56:05.144
It's not rocket science. but
you just got to make sure

00:56:05.231 --> 00:56:08.103
that if there's crime.
there's punishment.

00:56:08.190 --> 00:56:11.716
And none of the big boys ever
go down that are behind this.

00:56:11.803 --> 00:56:14.371
and you don't see
any middlemen caught.

00:56:14.458 --> 00:56:17.025
Certain tribes punch
way above their weight

00:56:17.112 --> 00:56:18.766
and just ignore the laws.

00:56:18.853 --> 00:56:21.508
The attractively dressed
people that the Western world

00:56:21.595 --> 00:56:25.251
loves so much are the worst
offenders in all of this.

00:56:27.601 --> 00:56:29.342
Lions used to be poisoned

00:56:29.429 --> 00:56:32.824
with a very readily available
cattle dip called Kopertox.

00:56:32.911 --> 00:56:35.783
Now they're use an insecticide.
which is even more virulent.

00:56:35.870 --> 00:56:38.830
called Furadan. which
comes from America.

00:56:38.917 --> 00:56:40.658
It's meant to be banned.
of course it isn't.

00:56:40.745 --> 00:56:41.963
you can buy it anywhere.

00:56:43.791 --> 00:56:46.490
And that's what comes with
the increase in stock numbers.

00:56:47.926 --> 00:56:50.885
- It starts with some lions
going into an enclosure.

00:56:50.972 --> 00:56:53.932
the residue carcass getting
spliced with this poison.

00:56:54.019 --> 00:56:57.501
The lions coming back. they
get killed. hyenas come in.

00:56:57.588 --> 00:56:59.851
they get killed. the
vultures come in.

00:56:59.938 --> 00:57:01.635
they get killed. it's horrific.

00:57:03.637 --> 00:57:07.162
Lions and leopards in
particular are very capable

00:57:07.249 --> 00:57:10.209
of jumping over and climbing
into these enclosures.

00:57:11.645 --> 00:57:14.996
Leopard in particular. they
go on kind of killing phase.

00:57:15.083 --> 00:57:17.129
It's like kill
everything that moves.

00:57:17.216 --> 00:57:20.567
The owner of that livestock
is not best pleased.

00:57:20.654 --> 00:57:22.090
to put it mildly.

00:57:22.177 --> 00:57:25.137
Many of them will kill
the offending leopard

00:57:25.224 --> 00:57:27.095
or kill the offending lion.

00:57:27.182 --> 00:57:29.533
Almost all these predators
don't like people.

00:57:29.620 --> 00:57:31.056
Elephants don't like people.

00:57:31.143 --> 00:57:33.275
Fully understandable.
we're the big baddies.

00:57:35.930 --> 00:57:38.237
Okay. Light for Life.
it's the deployment

00:57:38.324 --> 00:57:42.154
of a LED lighting system.
a flashing lighting system

00:57:42.241 --> 00:57:45.244
around the periphery of
livestock enclosures.

00:57:48.334 --> 00:57:50.031
[calf mooing]

00:57:50.118 --> 00:57:51.903
These flashing lights actually
represent human movement.

00:57:51.990 --> 00:57:54.166
activity within the enclosures.

00:57:55.646 --> 00:57:57.082
If you stop the predator

00:57:57.169 --> 00:57:59.650
going into the boma.
then there is no need

00:57:59.737 --> 00:58:01.565
for retaliatory killing.

00:58:01.652 --> 00:58:03.262
Then they don't need
to go out with a spear.

00:58:03.349 --> 00:58:04.742
They don't need to lay poison.

00:58:04.829 --> 00:58:06.395
They are prepared
to accept living

00:58:06.483 --> 00:58:10.748
in proximity...as they
have done for generations.

00:58:10.835 --> 00:58:13.490
[lion grunting]

00:58:56.010 --> 00:58:58.491
- For the last fifteen years.

00:58:58.578 --> 00:59:01.625
I've run my own safari
hunting company.

00:59:01.712 --> 00:59:03.714
which is basically
trophy hunting.

00:59:06.586 --> 00:59:08.153
I believe in hunting.

00:59:08.240 --> 00:59:11.243
I don't see anything wrong
in shooting an animal.

00:59:11.330 --> 00:59:16.204
I don't necessarily say you
should shoot a trophy animal.

00:59:17.989 --> 00:59:20.078
- [Director] Why are
animals trophies?

00:59:21.253 --> 00:59:25.518
- It's a memento of the
experience of the hunt.

00:59:25.605 --> 00:59:28.173
So you keep something
from your experience.

00:59:28.260 --> 00:59:31.959
Because the trophy hunting
fraternity likes to say

00:59:32.046 --> 00:59:34.396
that we're not just
there to kill something.

00:59:34.483 --> 00:59:35.528
it's about the experience.

00:59:35.615 --> 00:59:36.921
It's not about the trophy.

00:59:37.008 --> 00:59:38.705
It's all about being
in the wilderness

00:59:38.792 --> 00:59:40.141
and pursuing something.

00:59:42.579 --> 00:59:47.584
In many cases underage animals
will get shot. even females.

00:59:48.715 --> 00:59:50.456
Females are not
allowed to be shot.

00:59:52.284 --> 00:59:56.375
If you do shoot a female. it's
a transgression of the law.

00:59:56.462 --> 01:00:00.248
Certain species are very
susceptible to this. like lion.

01:00:00.335 --> 01:00:02.511
Because in the field.
it's incredibly easy

01:00:02.599 --> 01:00:03.817
to change the rules.

01:00:05.950 --> 01:00:09.649
There's no one around for
miles except the game scout.

01:00:09.736 --> 01:00:11.259
who works for me. I pay him.

01:00:13.261 --> 01:00:18.266
You'll do a hunt of 10 days.
that's 2.500 dollars you earn.

01:00:20.094 --> 01:00:24.708
$2.500 is a reasonable amount.
I believe. for 10 days.

01:00:24.795 --> 01:00:26.710
Some people don't
think so. so they rely

01:00:26.797 --> 01:00:29.147
on a gratuity at the
end of the safari.

01:00:30.714 --> 01:00:34.979
And so. the client would be.
"Well. why can't I shoot that?"

01:00:38.547 --> 01:00:40.593
So. then the professional
hunter starts thinking.

01:00:40.680 --> 01:00:42.900
well if I let him shoot it.

01:00:42.987 --> 01:00:44.815
maybe he'll give me
a better gratuity.

01:00:48.035 --> 01:00:50.516
You've got to weigh up
your ethics and your morals

01:00:50.603 --> 01:00:52.344
within an instant in the field.

01:00:52.431 --> 01:00:56.740
Everyone brands the term.
hunters are conservationists.

01:00:58.176 --> 01:01:01.527
They are in that sense.
but there's lots of hunters

01:01:01.614 --> 01:01:03.398
who don't stick to that.

01:01:03.485 --> 01:01:07.098
And look. mistakes happen.

01:01:07.185 --> 01:01:08.839
Lots of mistakes
have happened to me.

01:01:08.926 --> 01:01:11.145
If someone tells me. as
a professional hunter.

01:01:11.232 --> 01:01:14.496
they've never made a
mistake. they're lying.

01:01:14.583 --> 01:01:16.455
I'd call them a
liar to their face.

01:01:16.542 --> 01:01:18.587
You know things do happen.

01:01:18.675 --> 01:01:20.285
[tense music]

01:01:20.372 --> 01:01:25.377
Taking a photograph is.
you're just viewing.

01:01:26.334 --> 01:01:27.858
you're not
participating in action.

01:01:27.945 --> 01:01:32.427
And. the act of hunting
is not about killing.

01:01:33.559 --> 01:01:36.388
It's about that
participation in nature

01:01:36.475 --> 01:01:38.433
and with each individual animal.

01:01:41.306 --> 01:01:43.395
We as hunters tout. you know.

01:01:43.482 --> 01:01:45.223
"Hunting is conservation.

01:01:46.398 --> 01:01:48.705
"It's the best form
of conservation."

01:01:48.792 --> 01:01:50.532
What I've seen in my lifetime

01:01:50.619 --> 01:01:54.232
is that our wilderness areas
have just been depleted.

01:01:58.845 --> 01:02:00.673
- [Director] So when
you kill an animal.

01:02:00.760 --> 01:02:02.283
you don't think it's murder.
you don't think it's--

01:02:02.370 --> 01:02:06.026
- I cry. I've hunted
lion. every lion that one

01:02:06.113 --> 01:02:07.854
of my clients has taken. I cry.

01:02:07.941 --> 01:02:11.684
Because I. I feel
that it's not right

01:02:13.164 --> 01:02:17.821
to take that animal's life. he
has lived a life like I have.

01:02:18.909 --> 01:02:22.303
[dramatic music]

01:02:22.390 --> 01:02:24.828
When you're hunting antelope.
there's thousands of them.

01:02:24.915 --> 01:02:27.265
So. it's not a big event.

01:02:29.180 --> 01:02:34.185
The work and effort that goes
into the hunting of a lion

01:02:35.273 --> 01:02:37.623
is worthy of the
respect to the animal.

01:02:37.710 --> 01:02:39.059
For me. it's their life.

01:02:39.146 --> 01:02:40.757
Especially a male lion.

01:02:40.844 --> 01:02:44.238
they go through hardships.
they're survivors.

01:02:45.283 --> 01:02:46.893
Because they get
kicked out of the pride

01:02:46.980 --> 01:02:49.983
when they're two or three
years old and they have

01:02:50.070 --> 01:02:52.203
to make it on their own.

01:02:52.290 --> 01:02:55.946
When you find a male lion
that is past his prime.

01:02:56.033 --> 01:03:00.733
when he is nine. 10 years
old. he has been through

01:03:00.820 --> 01:03:05.782
so much in that span of time.
it's worthy of adoration.

01:03:09.263 --> 01:03:12.310
It sounds stupid
to now go kill him.

01:03:12.397 --> 01:03:15.139
but you know. that's
what we have to do.

01:03:15.226 --> 01:03:17.619
That's part of the system.

01:03:20.013 --> 01:03:24.409
The very first elephant
hunt I went on was

01:03:24.496 --> 01:03:28.239
with my stepfather and the
number of elephants he killed

01:03:28.326 --> 01:03:31.068
is insignificant to what
other people have done.

01:03:32.243 --> 01:03:34.288
We didn't boast about
shooting elephants.

01:03:35.855 --> 01:03:38.031
Before that. you know.
the great white hunters.

01:03:38.118 --> 01:03:40.773
they were shooting
thousands of elephants.

01:03:40.860 --> 01:03:43.428
They'd cut out the tusks
and cut out the heart

01:03:43.515 --> 01:03:45.778
and eat that and move on.

01:03:49.434 --> 01:03:52.002
- [Director] Why do people
want to eat the heart?

01:03:55.005 --> 01:03:56.528
- I would not personally
shoot an elephant

01:03:56.615 --> 01:03:57.834
just for its heart.

01:03:59.357 --> 01:04:02.360
But it. you know that's
the best tasting part

01:04:02.447 --> 01:04:03.927
of an elephant is the heart.

01:04:05.363 --> 01:04:07.800
But to go and kill an
elephant just to have that.

01:04:07.887 --> 01:04:11.630
no. you don't do that. [laughs]

01:04:14.633 --> 01:04:17.810
With an elephant once
it's dead. it's a process.

01:04:17.897 --> 01:04:19.290
You start butchering
the elephant.

01:04:19.377 --> 01:04:21.466
Now to cut through
the skin takes.

01:04:21.553 --> 01:04:23.555
maybe two hours to
get the skin off.

01:04:24.991 --> 01:04:28.908
When you reach the heart.
it's considered a delicacy.

01:04:28.995 --> 01:04:31.432
so you make a fire.
you cut it open.

01:04:31.519 --> 01:04:34.131
and you start cooking
it on the fire.

01:04:34.218 --> 01:04:35.610
And you put a bit of salt on it.

01:04:35.697 --> 01:04:38.962
and you start cutting
little bits off of it

01:04:39.049 --> 01:04:42.748
as you're working.
throughout the day.

01:04:49.929 --> 01:04:51.322
I wouldn't say I despise

01:04:51.409 --> 01:04:53.019
the trophy hunting
movement entirely.

01:04:53.106 --> 01:04:55.674
because it does
serve some function

01:04:55.761 --> 01:04:57.850
to bringing clients to Africa.

01:04:57.937 --> 01:05:01.985
Hunting is not about collecting
as many animals as you can.

01:05:02.072 --> 01:05:04.988
getting a gold Super
Bowl-style ring.

01:05:05.075 --> 01:05:07.207
And that is what the
largest hunting club

01:05:07.294 --> 01:05:09.166
in America promotes.

01:05:11.777 --> 01:05:14.867
They want you to shoot as
many animals as you can

01:05:14.954 --> 01:05:17.174
and then you become part
of the inner circle.

01:05:17.261 --> 01:05:18.218
and you get a ring.

01:05:21.352 --> 01:05:23.180
You get numerous
awards before that.

01:05:26.226 --> 01:05:29.447
But that is not what
hunting is about.

01:05:32.363 --> 01:05:36.497
The American hunter
thinks my 100.000 dollars

01:05:36.584 --> 01:05:38.978
that I've paid. all of that goes

01:05:39.065 --> 01:05:40.806
back into conservation.
it doesn't.

01:05:43.722 --> 01:05:44.636
Wow. look at that.

01:05:47.160 --> 01:05:51.425
- Oh yeah. we have
boxes and boxes.

01:05:51.512 --> 01:05:52.774
- [Director] What are those?

01:05:52.861 --> 01:05:54.080
- These are elephant
hair bracelets.

01:05:54.167 --> 01:05:55.821
- [Director] And
where are they from?

01:05:55.908 --> 01:05:58.302
- They're the hair that comes
from an elephant's tail.

01:05:59.694 --> 01:06:02.610
So they used to be very
popular. but I guess nowadays

01:06:02.697 --> 01:06:06.179
they're would be a social
issue with wearing them.

01:06:08.181 --> 01:06:11.576
You get about twenty
bracelets from a tail.

01:06:11.663 --> 01:06:15.232
- Just this one bag would
be five or six. right?

01:06:15.319 --> 01:06:20.324
Because there's a hundred.
there's 179 bracelets in here.

01:06:21.499 --> 01:06:22.848
- That's what we see
the most common thing

01:06:22.935 --> 01:06:24.719
on the elephant is
they chop the tusks out

01:06:24.806 --> 01:06:27.679
and take the tail. those
are the two parts they take.

01:06:29.507 --> 01:06:31.030
- [Director] How old
is that elephant?

01:06:32.249 --> 01:06:36.993
- An adolescent. maybe
twelve. twelve years.

01:06:38.342 --> 01:06:39.517
It's still a baby.

01:06:40.692 --> 01:06:43.434
It's not right.
that they end up.

01:06:43.521 --> 01:06:48.091
an elephant ends up for
this. to satisfy some.

01:06:48.178 --> 01:06:51.094
you know. put on
someone's mantelpiece.

01:06:51.181 --> 01:06:53.444
That's not what they're.
they're too majestic

01:06:53.531 --> 01:06:55.750
and special to end up here.

01:06:58.536 --> 01:07:00.538
[sighs]

01:07:01.582 --> 01:07:04.368
[dramatic music]

01:07:13.986 --> 01:07:16.554
[gun clicking]

01:07:20.036 --> 01:07:22.951
[wings fluttering]

01:07:25.911 --> 01:07:29.784
In terms of trophy hunting.
I don't do that anymore.

01:07:29.871 --> 01:07:31.482
- [Director] But you'll
take people to Africa.

01:07:31.569 --> 01:07:33.745
so. you're like a
middleman for murder.

01:07:34.615 --> 01:07:36.313
- Middleman for murder?

01:07:36.400 --> 01:07:37.749
I guess you could
look at it that way.

01:07:37.836 --> 01:07:40.447
that's an extreme
view. though. [laughs]

01:07:40.534 --> 01:07:41.970
Because. what do you call it?

01:07:43.842 --> 01:07:47.976
The. what do you call
it? The abattoir.

01:07:48.064 --> 01:07:50.153
murderous chain is
already set up there.

01:07:50.240 --> 01:07:53.156
So. rather have a
good guy doing it

01:07:53.243 --> 01:07:55.723
than a bad guy abusing it.

01:07:59.423 --> 01:08:02.382
In Africa. it's a
different situation

01:08:02.469 --> 01:08:06.343
with the trophy hunting because
the animals are utilized.

01:08:06.430 --> 01:08:08.301
The finances. the
money that comes in

01:08:08.388 --> 01:08:11.043
from the utilization
of those animals.

01:08:11.130 --> 01:08:13.872
gets put back into
conservation...theoretically.

01:08:14.742 --> 01:08:17.310
- [Director] But it doesn't.

01:08:17.397 --> 01:08:19.138
Who takes the money?

01:08:19.225 --> 01:08:22.272
- The majority of the money
that is made from trophy hunting

01:08:23.447 --> 01:08:27.103
remains within the
government circles.

01:08:27.190 --> 01:08:29.757
I would say. 70% remains

01:08:29.844 --> 01:08:31.933
within the circles
of administration.

01:08:36.416 --> 01:08:41.117
Game numbers are
often fabricated.

01:08:41.204 --> 01:08:44.555
because if you have
high game numbers

01:08:44.642 --> 01:08:48.515
it means you can
harvest more. you know.

01:08:48.602 --> 01:08:52.215
So. the utilization of the money

01:08:52.302 --> 01:08:57.263
that comes from hunting.
very little filters through

01:09:01.006 --> 01:09:02.573
to what it's intended for.

01:09:02.660 --> 01:09:06.272
It's intended to make
the communities living

01:09:06.359 --> 01:09:11.321
within those hunting areas
benefit: education. medical.

01:09:15.499 --> 01:09:19.590
an upliftment of their lives.
for not utilizing that land.

01:09:20.895 --> 01:09:24.377
And secondly. the
conservation of the animals.

01:09:24.464 --> 01:09:26.684
that money is meant to conserve.

01:09:28.207 --> 01:09:31.776
- People have become much more
environmentally conscious.

01:09:31.863 --> 01:09:33.517
much more green.

01:09:33.604 --> 01:09:35.562
And in particular when
it comes to something

01:09:35.649 --> 01:09:39.653
like African wildlife where you
read the shocking statistics

01:09:39.740 --> 01:09:42.178
and people want to do
something about it.

01:09:43.353 --> 01:09:46.269
So. when you're talking
about 75.000 dollars.

01:09:46.356 --> 01:09:49.359
for instance to hunt an
elephant. or to hunt a lion.

01:09:49.446 --> 01:09:52.100
or something like that.
most of that money

01:09:52.188 --> 01:09:54.146
is actually going to
the professional hunter.

01:09:54.233 --> 01:09:56.540
You've got the person
from the United States.

01:09:56.627 --> 01:09:59.847
often as not. who comes
here to hunt an animal.

01:09:59.934 --> 01:10:04.287
And he engages a hunting
safari operator here.

01:10:04.374 --> 01:10:07.638
a professional hunter. and
the bulk of that money goes

01:10:07.725 --> 01:10:11.946
to that individual: the
50. 60. 70.000 dollars.

01:10:12.033 --> 01:10:14.558
And only a small portion
of that actually goes

01:10:14.645 --> 01:10:17.909
to the government in
the form of the license

01:10:17.996 --> 01:10:21.565
that they pay for the
right to kill an animal.

01:10:21.652 --> 01:10:23.828
So. 4.500 dollars and they share

01:10:23.915 --> 01:10:26.178
that between the
communities in the area

01:10:26.265 --> 01:10:30.138
of the hunting concession.
So. it's peanuts.

01:10:31.966 --> 01:10:34.665
You're not going to get
hundreds of thousands

01:10:34.752 --> 01:10:36.101
of people coming to hunt.

01:10:36.188 --> 01:10:37.450
You're going to get
hundreds of thousands

01:10:37.537 --> 01:10:40.584
of people coming to
take photographs.

01:10:40.671 --> 01:10:43.848
Two things actually seem
obvious. to me anyway.

01:10:43.935 --> 01:10:45.806
One is that there should
be more of an emphasis

01:10:45.893 --> 01:10:49.854
on photographic safari
tourism and the second

01:10:49.941 --> 01:10:52.509
is that they ought
to raise the fee

01:10:52.596 --> 01:10:55.338
that they charge these
hunters to come in

01:10:55.425 --> 01:10:56.817
and hunt an animal.

01:10:58.036 --> 01:10:59.646
So. over the span
of its lifetime.

01:10:59.733 --> 01:11:01.866
a lion would generate three
and half million dollars

01:11:01.953 --> 01:11:05.348
in photographic safari
tourism revenue.

01:11:05.435 --> 01:11:07.350
An elephant is something
over a million.

01:11:08.742 --> 01:11:10.222
But the professional hunters
have to come to terms

01:11:10.309 --> 01:11:13.921
with the effects of
poaching on their industry.

01:11:14.008 --> 01:11:16.489
There just aren't that
many animals left anymore.

01:11:18.883 --> 01:11:22.060
- [Director] What was the
impetus to take hunting out

01:11:22.147 --> 01:11:23.627
of the safari business?

01:11:23.714 --> 01:11:26.064
- I have to go back
many. many years.

01:11:26.151 --> 01:11:28.196
Really. it almost goes
back to my childhood.

01:11:28.284 --> 01:11:30.764
I grew up in Africa.
we all hunted.

01:11:30.851 --> 01:11:32.418
it was a thing we just did.

01:11:34.159 --> 01:11:35.595
We hunted the Maasai Mara.

01:11:35.682 --> 01:11:38.163
where the Masaai Mara
game reserve is today.

01:11:38.250 --> 01:11:40.992
The climax of the whole safari
was to shoot an elephant.

01:11:42.167 --> 01:11:43.821
I shot the elephant.
the elephant charged.

01:11:43.908 --> 01:11:46.563
and the elephant died. literally
within a few feet of me.

01:11:47.999 --> 01:11:49.566
When I saw this elephant dead.

01:11:49.653 --> 01:11:53.091
it was like this horrendous
feeling came over me.

01:11:53.178 --> 01:11:54.527
- [Director] Did you cry?

01:11:54.614 --> 01:11:55.659
- I said. "How could
I have done this?"

01:11:55.746 --> 01:11:57.356
No. I didn't cry. I just felt.

01:11:57.443 --> 01:11:59.489
I just felt shocked. "How
could I have done this?"

01:11:59.576 --> 01:12:00.664
Beautiful animal. dead.

01:12:02.361 --> 01:12:03.928
There's something about a hunt.

01:12:04.015 --> 01:12:06.409
if you've done it. which
is very. very thrilling.

01:12:06.496 --> 01:12:08.367
You can't take the
higher ground here.

01:12:08.454 --> 01:12:10.456
oh. it's just terrible
to hunt. you know?

01:12:10.543 --> 01:12:11.762
Why do people hunt?

01:12:11.849 --> 01:12:13.111
Why?

01:12:13.198 --> 01:12:14.765
Because it's thrilling.
it's exciting.

01:12:14.852 --> 01:12:17.594
So. I said. "Well how can
I have an exciting feeling

01:12:17.681 --> 01:12:20.074
"about my safaris.
like when I was young?"

01:12:20.161 --> 01:12:22.425
So. I built the first
camp in the world.

01:12:22.512 --> 01:12:24.296
you see all these tented
camps all over the world?

01:12:24.383 --> 01:12:25.819
Mine was the first camp ever.

01:12:25.906 --> 01:12:27.038
- [Director] In Kenya?

01:12:27.125 --> 01:12:28.909
- No. in the world.

01:12:28.996 --> 01:12:33.349
And so I hit America. in about
1966. or '67. with a slogan:

01:12:34.219 --> 01:12:36.090
Hunt with a camera. not a gun.

01:12:36.177 --> 01:12:38.919
[plane roaring]

01:12:39.006 --> 01:12:42.532
[soaring. uplifting music]

01:12:43.533 --> 01:12:44.882
I felt like a missionary.

01:12:44.969 --> 01:12:46.971
I came all over saying
"No. don't hunt!"

01:12:48.407 --> 01:12:49.974
Have all the thrill of the
hunt. but at the last minute

01:12:50.061 --> 01:12:53.151
instead of going
bang. you'd go pop.

01:12:53.238 --> 01:12:55.022
and you'd have a
lovely picture forever.

01:12:56.459 --> 01:12:58.069
And I used to go and stay
with all the people in Texas

01:12:58.156 --> 01:13:00.463
and they had these huge
trophy rooms and I would say.

01:13:00.550 --> 01:13:04.162
"No. this over!" "No. we're
going on our next hunt. Geoff.

01:13:04.249 --> 01:13:05.642
"we're gonna do this.
why don't you come with?"

01:13:05.729 --> 01:13:07.644
And I said "No. no. no.
I've got this idea."

01:13:07.731 --> 01:13:09.297
And they go. "What the?

01:13:09.385 --> 01:13:11.474
"That sounds so pathetic.
that's a girl's thing.

01:13:11.561 --> 01:13:13.998
"Girls do photographs.
men hunt."

01:13:14.085 --> 01:13:16.087
And I said. "No. no
you have it wrong."

01:13:16.174 --> 01:13:17.480
So. what was better?

01:13:17.567 --> 01:13:19.438
To hunt. or to go
into photography?

01:13:19.525 --> 01:13:21.571
Everybody ridiculed
it. the answer was.

01:13:21.658 --> 01:13:24.269
"Of course. photography!"

01:13:24.356 --> 01:13:25.966
It was the best thing ever.

01:13:26.053 --> 01:13:27.490
- [Narrator] For
every $1.00 invested

01:13:27.577 --> 01:13:29.796
in protecting elephants
in East Africa.

01:13:29.883 --> 01:13:33.365
they get back $1.78
in tourism revenue.

01:13:34.584 --> 01:13:36.977
- Where are all the guys
who used to go hunting?

01:13:37.064 --> 01:13:38.283
Still running around
in their Toyotas.

01:13:38.370 --> 01:13:40.459
shooting a few
elephant. you know?

01:13:40.546 --> 01:13:42.330
[chain breaking]

01:13:42.418 --> 01:13:44.158
People who hunt always claim

01:13:44.245 --> 01:13:47.248
they're the most knowledgeable
conservationists on earth.

01:13:47.335 --> 01:13:49.381
They say that if
they weren't there.

01:13:49.468 --> 01:13:50.643
what would happen to the land?

01:13:50.730 --> 01:13:52.428
It would just go back to cattle.

01:13:52.515 --> 01:13:54.604
They say. "If we weren't
there policing our concession.

01:13:54.691 --> 01:13:58.085
"the poachers would come in
and eradicate all the animals."

01:13:58.172 --> 01:13:59.435
When I was born.

01:13:59.522 --> 01:14:01.480
there were 500.000
lions in Africa.

01:14:01.567 --> 01:14:03.308
I don't know how many there are.

01:14:03.395 --> 01:14:06.006
but we know 36.000 elephants
are being killed every year.

01:14:06.093 --> 01:14:07.225
We know that.

