- The chimpanzees were really
very helpful in helping me

01:23:03.848 --> 01:23:06.851
to convince. particularly
the scientific community.

01:23:06.938 --> 01:23:09.680
but other people as well.
that we humans are part

01:23:09.767 --> 01:23:12.248
of the animal kingdom.
Because chimpanzees

01:23:12.335 --> 01:23:14.163
are our closest
living relatives.

01:23:14.250 --> 01:23:18.428
And so when you then see
similarities in behavior

01:23:18.515 --> 01:23:20.082
it's pretty easy
for people to say.

01:23:20.169 --> 01:23:23.259
"Well yes. when chimpanzees
kiss and embrace

01:23:23.346 --> 01:23:26.479
"and hold hands and
pat one another.

01:23:26.566 --> 01:23:30.614
"they're probably feeling
similar emotions to us."

01:23:30.701 --> 01:23:33.486
When you see a chimpanzee
mother grieving the loss

01:23:33.573 --> 01:23:36.098
of her child. it's
pretty easy to say.

01:23:36.185 --> 01:23:39.536
"Well. the way they feel grief
must be similar to ours."

01:23:40.580 --> 01:23:42.713
- Jane Goodall
described a phenomenon

01:23:42.800 --> 01:23:44.410
that's found in Western
and Central Africa

01:23:44.497 --> 01:23:46.151
called Empty Forest Syndrome.

01:23:46.238 --> 01:23:48.588
And it's where the
forest is standing.

01:23:48.675 --> 01:23:51.113
but the wildlife has
largely disappeared.

01:23:51.200 --> 01:23:52.853
Why?

01:23:52.940 --> 01:23:56.161
And the answer to that is.
through the indiscriminate.

01:23:56.248 --> 01:23:59.773
commercial-scale hunting
of wildlife for bush meat.

01:23:59.860 --> 01:24:03.081
Wire snares are set to catch.
maybe they're set to catch

01:24:03.168 --> 01:24:06.911
small antelopes. but wire
snares will catch anything.

01:24:06.998 --> 01:24:09.653
Any animal that goes in
that will kill itself

01:24:09.740 --> 01:24:10.567
in its struggle to escape.

01:24:12.264 --> 01:24:15.050
[gorilla breathing]

01:24:17.748 --> 01:24:19.750
- They've already
got two snares here

01:24:21.230 --> 01:24:24.102
where they set their traps
on the routes of the animals

01:24:24.189 --> 01:24:25.625
when the animals
are going this way.

01:24:25.712 --> 01:24:27.845
They are going to the water.

01:24:27.932 --> 01:24:30.761
So they merely
locate their snares

01:24:32.023 --> 01:24:33.590
where specifically on
the route of the animals

01:24:33.677 --> 01:24:35.592
where they usually go to water.

01:24:39.030 --> 01:24:41.163
- What the poacher will
do. they have a game trail.

01:24:41.250 --> 01:24:43.121
and they set it across
trail like that.

01:24:43.208 --> 01:24:45.950
With this end
attached to a tree.

01:24:46.037 --> 01:24:47.691
So the animal will come through.

01:24:47.778 --> 01:24:49.867
they'll be foliage put on
each side to disguise it.

01:24:49.954 --> 01:24:53.436
it puts its head through
and it's just a slipknot.

01:24:54.611 --> 01:24:57.527
And as it goes forward
it just tightens.

01:24:58.789 --> 01:25:00.617
and as it pulls it
just strangles it.

01:25:02.445 --> 01:25:04.838
Sometimes they can take
hours and hours to die.

01:25:08.625 --> 01:25:10.235
- And why are they set?

01:25:10.322 --> 01:25:11.889
They're set for bush meat.

01:25:11.976 --> 01:25:14.283
The bush meat is then
sold in commercial centers

01:25:15.719 --> 01:25:18.461
and the people who do the
poaching are making a killing.

01:25:18.548 --> 01:25:20.158
A killing because
they kill the animals.

01:25:20.245 --> 01:25:22.552
But also. they didn't
raise the animal.

01:25:22.639 --> 01:25:25.381
they didn't have it
inoculated. they didn't feed it

01:25:25.468 --> 01:25:26.512
when there was a drought.

01:25:26.599 --> 01:25:28.906
Their cost is simply the piece

01:25:28.993 --> 01:25:32.257
of wire that they probably
stole off someone else's fence

01:25:32.344 --> 01:25:34.825
to kill this particular animal.

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:37.567
And the other thing
is that bush meat

01:25:37.654 --> 01:25:40.700
represents a potential
risk to human populations.

01:25:40.787 --> 01:25:42.702
It could be riddled
with anthrax.

01:25:42.789 --> 01:25:46.053
So. bush meat is a killer.
whichever way you look at it.

01:25:46.141 --> 01:25:47.751
[tense music]

01:25:47.838 --> 01:25:50.275
- If the hunting can be
controlled to some extent.

01:25:50.362 --> 01:25:53.148
a lot of these
primate populations

01:25:53.235 --> 01:25:55.106
have a good chance of surviving.

01:25:55.193 --> 01:25:56.716
The big problem now

01:25:56.803 --> 01:25:59.066
is this largely uncontrolled
bush meat hunting.

01:25:59.154 --> 01:26:01.112
And it's not a
subsistence issue.

01:26:01.199 --> 01:26:06.161
It's really. it's a luxury
trade. where chimp meat

01:26:07.640 --> 01:26:09.381
or gorilla meat or monkey
meat in the capital city

01:26:09.468 --> 01:26:12.428
sells for more than beef or
chicken or fish. in many cases.

01:26:12.515 --> 01:26:16.997
So. it's really.
really hard to control.

01:26:17.084 --> 01:26:20.262
Within remaining forest
areas. the poaching.

01:26:20.349 --> 01:26:22.568
whether it's for hunting
or for wildlife trade.

01:26:22.655 --> 01:26:25.354
it's just eliminating
the vast majority

01:26:25.441 --> 01:26:27.051
of species larger than a rat.

01:26:30.489 --> 01:26:32.274
So. you can go into the
forests in the Amazon

01:26:32.361 --> 01:26:34.101
and you can go into forests.

01:26:34.189 --> 01:26:36.278
certainly in Central and West
Africa where there's nothing.

01:26:36.365 --> 01:26:38.323
Nice forest. but nothing.

